es (`total_mismatches`).\\n    *   The mismatch check is performed inside the clocked `always` block.\\n    *   When a mismatch occurs, the queue is displayed *after* the element causing the mismatch has been pushed, following the queue display example structure.\\n    *   The final `final` block is rewritten to check if `total_mismatches` is zero and display the required success/failure message, using `first_mismatch_time`.\\n\\n5. **Maintaining Functionality:** All existing components (`stimulus_gen`, `RefModule` instantiation, clocking structure, timeout) are preserved exactly as in the golden testbench. The verification logic (`tb_match`) is kept but its reporting is integrated into the queue/counter mechanism.\\n\\n6. **Syntax Advice:** Ensure all queue elements are declared with the exact widths of the signals they hold (e.g., input queue holds 4 bits, output queue holds 1 bit). The queue management logic (`delete(0)` before `push_back()`) must be robustly implemented inside the clocked block.\\n\\n7. **Final Output:** Structure the result strictly as the required JSON object.",\n    "interface": "module TopModule (\\n    input logic [2:0] y,\\n    input logic w,\\n    output logic Y1\\n);\\n    // Module implementation goes here\\nendmodule",\n    "testbench": "`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\\n`define OK 12\\n`define INCORRECT 13\\n\\n// Stimulus Generator (Kept exactly as in golden TB)\\nmodule stimulus_gen (\\n\\tinput clk,\\n\\toutput reg [2:0] y,\\n\\toutput reg w\\n);\\n\\tinitial begin\\n\\t\\trepeat(100) @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\\n\\t\\t\\t{y,w} <= $random;\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t#1 $finish;\\n\\tend\\n\\tendmodule\\n\\n// Reference Module (Kept structure for compilation, implementation omitted)\\nmodule RefModule (\\n    input logic [2:0] y,\\n    input logic w,\\n    output logic Y1\\n);\\n    // Reference implementation\\nendmodule\\n\\n// Testbench with improved queue-based monitoring\\nmodule tb();\\n\\t// Statistics structure maintained from